Games We PlayUnit–III : Our Needs9
We all play games to entertain ourselves. The games that are played as 
competitions are known as sports.
Sports can be played in two ways – individually or as a team. The games in 
which a player plays alone against another player are called individual games 
such as archery, javelin throw, chess etc. whereas the games in which a team 
of players play against another team are called team games/sports such as 
cricket, hockey, football etc.
Let's KnowLet's KnowEnvironmental Studies-563

halt, Ayana and some other girls got down with a huge shining trophy and 
everyone burst into claps and cheers. Everyone was hugging them and shaking 
hands with them.
Can you guess, what was happening at the bus stand?
Well, the girls kabaddi team of Vista Public School had just returned after winning 
the state level inter school Kabaddi Championship!
A team represents an institution, state or country. A team sport cannot be played 
until each player feels parts of the team. A team sport has many advantages. It 
helps the players to grow and become more disciplined. Team sports encourage 
leadership qualities, sportsmanship and cooperation, so that players learn to face 
healthy competition. Team sports build social skills and help people make new 
friends.
National TeamA national team is defined as a team which represents a nation. The national team 
consists of players from all parts of the country. Though, they belong to different 
castes and religions, but when they go out to play for their country, they have only 
one identity, and that is their nationality.
When a national team gives an impressive performance in an international event, 
the whole country cheers the team and celebrates its victory. Thus, the 
performances of national teams unite the people of country.
Stars of IndiaIndia is a sports loving nation. There are many sports which have gained 
widespread popularity in India, e.g. hockey, boxing, 
shooting, wrestling, cricket, etc. Besides, many 
players also get international fame in their games.

Safety During CalamitiesUnit–IV : My Neighbourhood10Natural CalamitiesThe calamities that occur due to natural forces are called natural calamities.
Cyclones, floods, earthquakes, droughts, tsunamis are some forms of natural 
calamities or disasters.
Cyclones— These are strong winds rotating inwards. 
The wind speed can reach sometimes higher than 
100 km per hour. These winds uproot trees and 
cause great destruction. A cyclone is especially 
dangerous in coastal areas because it can lead to a 
A sudden event that causes great damage to life and property is called a 
disaster or calamity. Calamities are of two types— Natural Calamities and 
Man-made calamities.
Let's KnowLet's KnowEnvironmental Studies-571

sudden rise in the level of the sea causing floods. This causes heavy loss to human 
life, livestock and property.
Floods— Sometimes when rivers overflow due to 
excessive rains, floods occur. Floods can also occur 
due to breaking of dams or fast melting of glaciers. 
Due to floods, crops are damaged which may lead to 
famines. After the flood, many water-borne diseases 
such as cholera, typhoid, malaria, jaundice etc. also 
claim many lives.
Droughts— Droughts are a natural calamity that 
result from failing monsoon. When there is shortage 
of water, crops are unable to grow which causes 
famine. Because of scarcity of water and food, 
human beings and domestic animals die in large 
numbers and the general population suffers from 
hunger and poverty. 
Earthquakes— A sudden, violent shaking or trembling of the earth's surface is 
called an Earthquake. It is caused by severe shock 
waves which move under the ground, travel through 
rocks and reach the surface. These waves are called 
seismic waves. The intensity, direction and duration 
of an earthquake is recorded by an instrument called 
seismograph. The scale used to measure its intensity 
is called Richter Scale. Some earthquakes are so mild 
The cyclone Remal hit India recently. It occurred in Bay of Bengal during 
the 2024 pre-monsoon season.
In 2013, a multiday cloud burst centered on the North Indian state of 
Uttarakhand caused devastating floods and landslides that 
destroyed several villages and towns. Thousands of people were 
swept away, and many bodies were never recovered. It is regarded 
as the most worst natural disaster in India.

(Knowledge)Environmental Studies-572

that they are hardly felt but violent earthquakes destroy buildings and bury people 
under the debris. Dams may burst and cause floods. All this may lead to large scale 
destruction. Earthquakes measuring above 5 on Richter Scale can be devastating.
The Nepal earthquake of 25 April, 2015 was a strong one, measuring 7.8 
magnitudes on the Richter Scale.
Tsunamis— A Tsunami is a giant sea wave which is caused by an earthquake or 
volcanic eruption on the floor of the sea i.e. 
underwater. The waves can reach a height of 100 
feet, and have a terrific speed and crush everything 
in their path.
The Tsunami waves have a devastating effect. 
Houses and buildings are reduced to rubble. It 
claims scores of human lives and live-stock.
The Tsunami of 26 December, 2004 which hit the coasts of Sumatra, Indonesia, 
Sri Lanka and the Indian provinces of Andaman Islands and Tamil Nadu, was a 
devastating one. Nearly 3 lakhs people died or were missing and the total 
damage caused was calculated to be around 20 billion dollars.
Volcanic Eruption— It is a fissure or vent in the 
earth through which lava flows out. Lava may 
contain rocks, steam and gases. It is very hot. The 
eruption of a volcano can cause large scale 
destruction.
Epidemics and PandemicsWhen natural calamities occur, communicable diseases are sure to follow. This is 
because germs grow in unhygienic conditions that prevail after the calamity. 
Communicable diseases such as cholera, malaria and plague spread very fast. 
Many people start falling sick, causing a large number of deaths in a very short 
period of time. This sudden spread of disease in a large number of people in a 
specific area is called an Epidemic.
Environmental Studies-573

If the disease spreads to multiple areas or the entire globe, it is known as 
Pandemic. Multiple pandemics have occurred throughout history. The COVID-19 
pandemic (2020-2023)was the most recent pandemic which affected the whole 
world badly.
Prevention— We can control such epidemics by taking preventive measures. 
Improvement in community sanitation, health services, immunization 
programmes and hygienic practices are some measures that can control the 
outbreak of any epidemic.
Human-Made CalamitiesThere are certain calamities that are caused due to human activities, the 
involvement of humans or their negligence.
Bhopal Gas Tragedy (December 4, 1984), Jilin Chemical Explosion (November 13, 
2005), Deepwater Horizon Oil spill (April 20,2010) are some examples of human-made disasters/ calamities. Wars and terrorist attacks also come under this 
category.
Help in Times of CalamitiesSeveral government and non-government organization rescue the afffected 
people when calamity strikes and ruins the lives.
Government Organizations– Several government agencies like Defence forces, 
the National Disaster Relief Force, police, hospitals, firefighters etc. come forward 
to rescue the affected people. 
Epidemics can occur even when there is no natural calamity. They occur 
because of man's unhygienic practices. The plague epidemic in Surat 
(Gujarat) in 1994 is an example of this.
You 
 KnowMust 
(Knowledge)Environmental Studies-574

Our soldiers in such odd times not only rescue people but also provide food and 
medicines to affected areas.
Non-Government Organizations– Various national and international non-government organizagions also provide aid and support to the affected people. 
They collect donations and other utility items and distribute them to the people 
who are affected. Some such organizations are–
! United Nations children's Fund (UNICEF)
! The Oxford Committee for Famine Relief (OXFAM)
! Indian Red Cross Society.
! Volunteers for India Development. (VIDE)
! Fight and Drought Fund.
! Child Relief and You (CRY)
! World Health Organization (WHO)Safety Measures During Calamities
! Pay close attention to the weather alerts.
! Move to some safer places.
! Keep a waterproof emergency bag ready with dry food, water and medicines.
! Keep a torch handy. Stay calm.
! Keep a diary and note down the phone numbers of your local doctors, fire 
brigade, ambulance, hospitals, police stations and other organizations that 
help in emergencies.
! Call for help as soon as you sense the danger.
Prime Minister's National Relief Fund in India is the fund raised to 
provide support to the people affected by natural and man-made 
disasters.

like road closure updates, evacuation routes,
